    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `The age of the patient, the acute onset of the presentation, and the history of OCP use make a ruptured hepatic adenoma the most likely diagnosis. Hepatocellular adenomas (HCAs), also known as hepatic adenomas or liver cell adenomas, are rare, benign tumors of epithelial origin that affect less than 0.004% of the population at risk. HCAs occur mostly in women of childbearing age and are strongly associated with the use of oral contraceptive pills (OCPs) and other estrogens. This is reflected by a dramatic increase in the incidence of this disease since OCPs were introduced in the 1960s. The clinical presentation varies widely. Main features in the history and physical examination may include the following: pain in the right upper quadrant or epigastric region in 25-50% of patients with HCAs; patients may notice lesions as a palpable mass, lesions may also be discovered incidentally during an abdominal imaging study for an unrelated reason; history of birth control or anabolic steroid use should be checked in patients with suspected hepatocellular adenomas; patients may present with severe, acute abdominal pain with bleeding into the abdomen, which results in signs of shock such as hypotension, tachycardia, and diaphoresis; hemoperitoneum occurs more frequently if the patient is taking a high-dose OCP, actively menstruating, pregnant, or within six weeks postpartum. The location of the lesion is also important, with those near the surface of the liver more prone to causing hemoperitoneum. Option A: A strangulated hernia is unlikely to present with this clinical picture and an acute onset. Option B: Mesenteric artery occlusion is usually seen in older patients with thrombosis or embolus formation risk factors. A concomitant medical condition, such as atrial fibrillation, often predisposes the patient to embolus formation. The condition presents with postprandial diarrhoea, abdominal pain, and abdominal exam findings that are usually disproportionate to the symptoms. Rectal bleeding may be found on a digital rectal exam. Option C: Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is a disease seen in older male patients. Rupture of an AAA may present similarly; however, the age and gender of this patient make this diagnosis very unlikely. Option E: Acute appendicitis presents with vague periumbilical pain that gradually localizes in the right lower quadrant. Symptoms of peritonitis and shock develop later following rupture of the inflamed appendix. Acute appendicitis is a very unlikely explanation for this presentation.`,
