    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Iron studies are the most appropriate initial investigation when hemochromatosis is suspected clinically. The patient's presentation of polyarthritis, impotence, and decreased libido are consistent with hemochromatosis, which causes iron overload and deposition in multiple organ systems. Hemochromatosis presents with chronic hepatitis and cirrhosis (most common cause of mortality), arthralgia (often MCPs and large joints due to chondrocalcinosis and pseudogout), skin darkening (tanned skin from iron deposition), small testes/infertility/impotence/decreased libido (due to hypopituitarism and/or liver disease), diabetes mellitus (bronze diabetes), restrictive cardiomyopathy, panhypopituitarism, hepatocellular carcinoma (10% of cases with liver involvement), osteoporosis (25%) and osteopenia (41%), sparse body hair (62%), and spoon nails (50%). Transferrin saturation (ratio of serum iron to iron binding capacity) >45% is the most sensitive test for detecting early iron overload. Ferritin can be elevated in response to physiologic stresses, alcohol consumption, and liver disease, making it less accurate. HFE gene testing should be considered next if iron studies are abnormal on more than one occasion.`,
