    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Primary eosinophilic esophagitis (EoE) is an increasingly recognized condition characterized clinically by symptoms related to esophageal dysfunction and histologically by eosinophilic inflammation in the esophagus. EoE is hypothesized to be an atopic inflammatory disease caused by abnormal immune response to antigenic stimulation, mostly foods. Eosinophils are normally a component of mucosal infiltrates in all-length of the gastrointestinal tract except the esophagus; eosinophils in the esophageal mucosa are always pathologic. Clinical symptoms are nonspecific and patients are in good physical condition, resulting in delayed diagnosis (years) in some cases. In children, symptoms include nausea, vomiting, weight loss, anemia, and failure to thrive. In neonates and infants, food refusal is most common. In adults, characteristic symptoms include dysphagia for solid foods, retrosternal pain, and food impaction. Some patients present with GERD symptoms unresponsive to medical anti-reflux therapy. A subset has been recognized with typical EoE presentation in absence of GERD who show clinicopathologic response to PPIs (PPI-responsive EoE). According to ACG diagnostic criteria for EoE: symptoms related to esophageal dysfunction, ≥15 eosinophils/hpf on esophageal biopsy, persistence of eosinophilia after PPI trial, and secondary causes of esophageal eosinophilia excluded. This patient has symptoms and established eosinophilia on histology. For EoE diagnosis, eosinophilia must persist after 8-week PPI trial. GERD may mimic EoE, coexist with it, or contribute to it. Therefore, diagnosis of EoE is generally made after symptoms persist after 8-week PPI course as best initial step. PPIs may benefit EoE patients by reducing acid production in co-existent GERD or unknown anti-inflammatory mechanisms. Topical swallowed steroids (fluticasone, budesonide) are main treatment options once EoE diagnosis is established after failed PPI therapy or normal pH studies. Oral (systemic) prednisone may be indicated for patients unresponsive to PPI or swallowed corticosteroids.`,
