    explanation: `The clinical picture highly suggests bile duct obstruction (CBD). CBD obstruction presents with obstructive jaundice and often a palpable mass (distended gallbladder) in the right upper quadrant that can be tender or non-tender, depending on underlying etiology. The most common causes of CBD obstruction are: stones (most common), strictures, and periampullary tumors—these tumors arise within 2cm of the ampulla of Vater in the duodenum and include: pancreatic head/uncinate process tumors (pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma involving head and uncinate process of pancreas), lower common bile duct tumors (cholangiocarcinoma involving intra-pancreatic distal bile duct), ampullary tumors (originating from ampulampullaater), and periampullary duodenal carcinoma. Pancreatic head tumors are the most common periampullary tumors, but not in this case, as sonography shows the pancreatic head is clear; therefore, other types of periampullary tumors should be considered the most likely diagnosis. Chronic pancreatitis presents with abdominal pain, malabsorption, and diarrhea. Obstructive jaundice is not a presentation. Tumors of the pancreatic tail are far from the biliary system and do not cause biliary obstruction. Biliary cirrhosis does not cause CBD obstruction. Budd-Chiari syndrome is a thrombotic occlusion of hepatic veins, presenting a different clinical picture.`,
