    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Rectal bleeding is often caused by benign conditions such as hemorrhoids or anal fissures. However, this assumption may mask serious and more proximal pathologies such as colorectal cancer. To avoid missing patients with sinister conditions, either as the cause of bleeding or a concomitant problem, all such patients should be assessed even if, based on history, the etiology is apparent. The approach to patients with rectal bleeding starts with thorough history followed by physical exam. Physical examination should be directed at identifying possible or definite sources of bleeding and finding worrisome distal lesions that may be detectable. A detailed physical examination must include external inspection of the anus and a digital rectal exam as initial investigations. Having the patient bear down during examination may induce prolapse of a hemorrhoid or bleeding of a superficial lesion. Moreover, office-based anoscopy or proctoscopy should be performed in patients with acute rectal bleeding when available. These are simple measures that do not require bowel preparation. Sigmoidoscopy (options C and D) or colonoscopy (option E) is indicated in patients whose initial assessment suggests more proximal lesions as the cause.`,
