    explanation: `The clinical presentation is consistent with acute cholangitis. The patient initially presented with right-sided abdominal pain, mild jaundice, and fever (Charcot's triad). After 3 hours, she developed rigors and chills with worsening vital signs including hypotension (90/60 mmHg), tachycardia (110 bpm), and higher fever (39.5°C), indicating progression to sepsis. Acute cholangitis is a clinical syndrome characterized by fever, abdominal pain, and jaundice, developing due to stasis and infection in the biliary tract. It can rapidly progress to sepsis. The classic presentation includes Charcot's triad (fever, jaundice, and right upper quadrant pain). When hypotension and altered mental status are added, it becomes Reynolds' pentad, indicating septic shock. Biliary system obstruction is the most common predisposing factor.`,
