    explanation: `This patient has significantly increased direct (conjugated) bilirubin, and the rest of her liver function tests (ALT, ASD, ALP) are normal. In the presence of the hepatic black granular pigmentation of the hepatocytes in a liver biopsy, these suggest the Dubin–Johnson syndrome as the most likely diagnosis. Dubin-Johnson syndrome is a benign hereditary condition characterised by chronic or intermittent conjugated (direct) hyperbilirubinemia due to a defect in hepatocellular bilirubin excretion. In this condition, indirect (unconjugated) bilirubin is converted to direct (conjugated) bilirubin in hepatocytes, but it cannot be excreted in the biliary system. This results from mutations in the canalicular multidrug resistance protein 2 (MRP2) transporters, which impair biliary excretion of conjugated bilirubin and cause conjugated hyperbilirubinemia. The liver is grossly black due to epinephrine metabolites in the lysosomes of hepatic cells. The prognosis is excellent, so no treatment other than minimising exposure to triggers is needed. The condition is commonly seen in Jewish patients, and presents with jaundice and nonspecific complaints (fatigue, abdominal pain, malaise). The jaundice is mild and usually only becomes apparent during an illness or oral contraceptive use. Gilbert syndrome (Option A) and Crigler–Najjar syndrome (Option D) cause unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia rather than conjugated. Haemolytic anaemia (option B) results in indirect (unconjugated) hyperbilirubinemia, and hepatitis (option C) would have been associated with deranged liver function tests (ALT, AST) due to damage to hepatocytes and biliary system.`,
