    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Option B is correct. A colonoscopy should be performed one year after the resection of sporadic cancer unless a complete post-operative colonoscopy has been performed sooner. Recommendations for familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP) and hereditary nonpolyposis colorectal cancers (HNPCC) are different from sporadic cancers. If a perioperative colonoscopy performed at one year reveals advanced adenoma, the next colonoscopy should be performed in three years. If the colonoscopy performed at one year is normal or identifies no advanced adenomas, the next colonoscopy should be performed in five years. Since this man has not had a colonoscopy in the past ten years, he should undergo one now. Apart from colonoscopy according to the above recommendations, patients undergoing either local excision or advanced adenomas or ultra-low anterior resection for rectal cancer should be considered for periodic examination of the rectum at 6-month intervals for 2-3 years with digital rectal examination, rigid proctoscopy, flexible proctoscopy, and/or rectal endoscopic ultrasound. These examinations are considered to be independent of the colonoscopic examination schedule described above. Option A (abdominal CT scan) and Option D (CEA) are acceptable surveillance options but not as crucial as colonoscopy. Option E (sigmoidoscopy) cannot visualize beyond the sigmoid colon. Patients with a history of colon cancer need to have visualization of their entire colon for possible tumors or premalignant lesions by colonoscopy.`,
