    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Option A is correct. The HFE gene is involved in hereditary hemochromatosis (HH). Mutations in the HFE gene can lead to impaired regulation of iron storage and clinical manifestations of hemochromatosis. There are two types of mutation in the HFE gene: C282Y and H63D. Terminology: Those with only one copy of the mutated HFE (either C282Y or H63D) gene are called heterozygotes. Those with two copies of a C282Y mutation are called 'homozygotes.' Since those with two copies of an H63D mutation never develop clinical hemochromatosis, a homozygote refers to a person with two copies HFE with C282Y mutation only. Those with one copy of an HFE gene with a C282Y mutation and the other with an H63D mutation are called 'compound heterozygotes.' These individuals are often asymptomatic, and if symptoms are present, they are mild. About 90% of people of Northern European ancestry with symptoms of HH have the C282Y mutation in both copies of their HFE gene (homozygote). Two percent are compound heterozygotes. Since HH follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, there is often no family history, and affected family members may appear scattered over the generations. If both parents are heterozygous (carriers for a mutation in the HFE gene), there is a 25% chance that their children will be affected and genetically predisposed to HH. This woman's brother is diagnosed with hereditary hemochromatosis, meaning that both their parents have been at least carriers of HFE gene mutation. She can be a heterozygote, homozygote or compound heterozygote. Genetic testing will reveal that. It is recommended that first-degree and second-degree relatives of individuals who have HH or are homozygous for the C282Y gene mutation are tested with iron studies and the HFE gene test. Based on the recommendation, she needs testing. Further steps depend on her test results: If she does not have a faulty HFE gene, no further testing of the children would be indicated because even if the father is homozygote, the children would only be carriers in the worst-case scenario. If she is found to be homozygote, the next step would be testing the father. If the father is found to have no HFE mutations the children are not at risk of HH and could only be carriers, not susceptible to HH. Of the options, testing the mother for HH would be the next best step in management.`,
