    explanation: `The gene HFE gene is involved in hereditary hemochromatosis (HH). Mutations in the HFE gene can lead to impaired regulation of iron storage and clinical manifestations of hemochromatosis. There are two types of mutation in the gene: C282Y and H63D. Those with only one copy of the mutated HFE (either C282Y or H63D) gene are called heterozygotes. Those with two copies of the C282Y mutation are called 'homozygotes.' Since individuals with two copies of the H63D mutation never develop clinical hemochromatosis, the homozygote refers to a person with both copies of HFE with C282Y mutation only. Those with one copy of the HFE gene with a C282Y mutation and the other with an H63D mutation are called 'compound heterozygotes.' These individuals are often asymptomatic, and if symptoms are present, they are mild. About 90% of people of Northern European ancestry with symptoms of HH have the C282Y mutation in both copies of their HFE gene (homozygote). Two percent are compound heterozygotes. Since HH follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern, there is often no family history, and affected family members may appear scattered over the generations. If both parents are heterozygous (carriers for a mutation in the HFE gene), there is a 25% chance that their children will be affected and genetically predisposed to HH. Current guidelines advise that first-degree and second-degree relatives of individuals who have HH or are homozygous for the C282Y gene mutation should be tested with iron studies and the HFE gene test. Based on this recommendation, both children should be considered for testing; however, in this case, testing the mother would be more convenient and reasonable. If she does not have a faulty HFE gene, no further testing of the children would be indicated because even if the father is homozygote, the children would only be carriers in the worst-case scenario.`,
